\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab The Goodwill in Peter\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s town in much like the one in yours.  There\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s a rack of men's suitcoats by the door, a labrynth of used furniture where college roomattes argue over the dimensions of door frames, a housewares section where young newlyweds search for matching mugs without chips.  In fact, if you were standing behind him in line, you may be inclined to think that you were in your town.  There would be only one major difference - the things on the racks of your Goodwill are from the lives of the people in your town; the things on the racks around Peter are from the lives of the people in his town.  At first thought that might seem a trivial distinction, but I assure you, it is not.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Peter studied the pair of used gloves in his hands.  They were absolutely perfect.  Dried dirt still filled the wrinkles and crevices formed by someone else\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s hands; even when held flat in front of him the fingers clutched an invisible garden tool, a permanent hook worn by someone else\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s labor.  This was a prime selling point - he needed to look like he knew what he was doing, like this was not his first time working outside.  The gloves, he was convinced, were all the camoflauge one needed.  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Peter\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s stomach rumbled unhappily.  It was taking longer than Peter had expected to check out.  The store bustled for a Friday afternoon - mainly parents and children, a few elderly, but no one near his age.  He knew this to be the last day of classes for high school, and as far as college, Peter had never gotten far enough to know when they were let out.  He had done nothing in the year since he had graduated high school.  Not nothing, obviously - he passed his time going to the gym, shopping at Goodwill, driving his car around his increasingly familiar city.  But that was about it.  Peter could have written his plans for the week on a post-it - it would have read \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Gloves, hamburger\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 .\tab }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab In the parking lot Peter attempted to get his bag and body into his car without touching any of the hot surfaces, like a reverse game of Operation.  The car, a Daewoo Lanos, sat so close to the ground on its tiny wheels that he was forced to more or less fall into the open door.  He felt silly inside the car.  It was a small green hatchback, resembling a Spearmint tic-tac on wheels; it was ten years old, out of production, unrepairable, and above all, extremely ridiculous looking.  Perhaps the only positive was that whoever had owned it first had not seemed to care much for blarring loud music - the speakers sang clearly.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Peter scanned the parking lot pensively - still, no one near his age.  He relaxed, rolled the windows down, and turned the volume knob up slowly - }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Why do you build me up - }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Buttercup baby, just to let me down}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab And mess me around}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab He nodded his head happily as the wheels rolled into motion.  Time for stop two of the day.  Not far from the Goodwill was Hamburger Stand  - a dirt cheap alternative to conventional food situated across the street from a strip club.  Today the casual dining experience was enhanced by a car wash taking place across the street - half a dozen bikini-clad women wielding cartoon-sized sponges took turns half-heatedly wiping down cars as three or more stood at the corner, wringing water out over themselves dramatically.  When Peter walked in, the entire male populace sat facing the window, some squinting through vinyl stickers of hot dogs to make out the seductive shapes at work.  At the counter a man struggled to order with one eye transfixed at the scene outside.  \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Yeah, I\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll have the uh . . . do you guys still have the, uh . . .\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Peter\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s eyes lit up when he saw the jukebox in the corner.  \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Wow,\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  he expressed loudly to himself, \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Does that - I wonder if it works.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0   He jangled about eight dollars worth of quarters in his pocket as he approached the machine.  \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Wow, look at all this old music.  I wonder if I have any change.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab He did this almost ever Saturday.  And while the the process was becoming more streamlined for him - B7, A3, D4, A2 - it was becoming increasingly confusing behavoir to the people who worked the weekend shifts at Hamburger Stand.  \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 It\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s that guy . . .\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 , they whispered to eachother as he sunk quarter after quarter into the machine, his fingers rehersing familiar choreography on the glowing plastic buttons.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Sitting down to the the first snare hit of \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Blue Days, Black Nights\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 , Peter engrossed himself fully in his burger, in a corner facing the jukebox.  Those speakers worked pretty well too.  With his two major tasks for the week out of the way, Peter was finally able to relax.}
